land","St Nicholas' Church, Ipswich, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"St Nicholas' Church, Ipswich, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","London, England, United Kingdom":"London, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cage","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (East Anglia): from Middle English, Old French <i>cage</i> ‘cage, enclosure’ (from Latin <i>cavea</i> ‘container, cave’), denoting someone who lived by or was the keeper of a cage, in the sense ‘lock-up, prison for petty offenders’.","English: alternatively, a variant of   Keech  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Keech","meanings":["English (mainly Bedfordshire and Northamptonshire):","nickname for an fat person, from Middle English <i>cach</i>, <i>caiche</i>, <i>cage</i>, <i>kech</i>, a word of unexplained origin but presumably the antecedent of modern English dialect <i>keech</i> (variant <i>catch</i>) ‘lump of congealed fat; fat of a slaughtered animal rolled up into a lump (in preparation for sending to the chandler or tallow maker to make wax)’.","variant of <b>Kedge</b>, a nickname either from Middle English <i>kegge</i>, <i>kigge</i> ‘cheerful, pleasant, agreeable, merry’, or from an unrecorded Middle English <i>kegge</i> ‘belly’, for a pot-bellied person."]},{"name":"Cager","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Antoine.","English (Sussex): occupational name for a maker of cages or a jailer, Middle English <i>cager</i> (from Old French <i>cagier</i>), an agent derivative of   Cage  .","English: alternatively, a topographic name for someone who lived by a cage, equivalent to <i>atte Cage</i> (see   Cage  )."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705207,"age":1,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":3,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705212,"age":36,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705213,"age":58,"year":"1642","toYear":"1651","julianDay":2320789,"title":"The English Civil War","description":"A series of conflicts regarding England's governance during the years 1642 to 1651 is now known as The English Civil War. Charles I summoned supporters to join him against his enemies in Parliament. In October 1642, nearly 10,000 men fought for Charles I and chased Parliament across the River Tamar. Fighting continued for years and was finally ended at the Battle of Worcester on 